            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I didn't realise it would go through a temporary variable.\n\nAt least that has an advantage in making C macros more reliable in some cases where re-application is a risk. Other than these macros here, that is.\n\n> if it can be done simply it might be worthwhile.\n\nI also wouldn't mind adding these, although with a note in the documentation that they should be used with care because they can have an adversarial impact on performance when the chances of hitting a likely or unlikely case don't differ largely. Solid benchmarking is key here.\n\nI'm not sure this is entirely easy to add, though. The `IfClauseNode` in `Nodes.py` allows setting a `.branch_hint` (`\"likely\"` / `\"unlikely\"`), so injecting it at that level would be quite easy, but users could also try to mark parts of conditions as likely/unlikely and that might not work at all (as the OP suggested for clang) or might work by accident (if Cython ends up evaluating the condition in partial C if-statements). We'd want to trigger a user visible warning only for the cases where it might not work depending on the C compiler – or make sure that conditions marked as likely/unlikely _are_ evaluated as partial if-statements.\n\nTo keep things simpler, we could allow `cython.unlikely()` / `cython.likely()` markers only around complete if-clause conditions. The `TransformBuiltinMethods` tree visitor would make the if-clause nodes inhale the branch hint calls as a special case, and the translation would fail if such a call remains in the tree after that phase.\n",
